commentBody:
@Marshall Walthew 

I got INOUYE with a few crosses, but not because his name was a mystery to me.  There were several people I could think of, and I was puzzled as to what made him the [Highest-ranking Asian-American politician before Harris].

In the early 2010s, he was president pro tem of the Senate for about 2½ years, which put him very high in the line of Presidential succession.  Somehow, I didn't remember that fact, and thought he had equal standing with any number of US Senators.

@Dan Suzio 

Oof. That’s the kind of thing that can really slow you down. 

I don’t remember for certain, but I think that by the time I read the clue, I had enough letters to know it was Senator INOUYE.

@Steve L
This threw me at first, because I didn’t remember his service as President Pro Tem in the Senate. That would definitely place him higher in the Presidential succession order than any of the cabinet members I first considered.

By the way, he is buried in a rather plain grave in the National Cemetery of the Pacific near Honolulu. The marker notes his Medal of Honor.

@Sam Lyons 

If it had just been my husband and me, I’d have be happy getting to the resort by 10-ish. It’s a 90 minute drive from Durango; our early-rising friend was staying in South Fork, which is half an hour east of Wolf Creek. 

The way I figure it, if you know your legs are only good for four to six hours, why knock yourself out to get started as soon as the lifts are running? (We knew they didn’t have any fresh snow, so we wouldn’t have missed any untracked powder.)

@Eric Hougland 

Ah, to hark back to the good ole’ days 25 years ago when the beginning of December was a sure thing for snow. 

At any rate, it’s a gorgeous drive from Durango, even if you were doing half of it in the dark on your way out. I’m envious. I’ve seen snow exactly once this winter so far.

@Sam Lyons 

We stopped in Pagosa Springs for an early dinner, which put us back on US 160 at sunset. And it was pretty darned gorgeous. 

My biggest issue with driving at twilight is the deer. We saw two virtually in our front yard as we were leaving the house, a big buck on the west side of Pagosa Springs, and a bunch of others in various spots between here and Wolf Creek. I do not want to hit one.

@Eric Hougland 

Speaking of snow and Colorado’s four-legged, er, critters. The Dog and I were driving from Salt Lake to NM some years back, and my mother decided to come with us, so, to entertain her, I decided to get off the normal route outside Moab and detour through Silverton. There was so much snow it was like driving through white tunnels. We pulled off for a pit stop for The Dog and right there next to us, pretty as you please, were two mountain goats. Just hanging out on a crag maybe 30 feet from us, completely unafraid. What a sight. (Mighty Dog missed them completely, what with being on the short side and getting buried in all that snow.)

Your post has made me very wistful for my native snow country.

@jp inframan 

It has the wordplay question mark in the clue.

And here I was going to make the comment it was potentially to literal of an answer for that. I guess not...

@Steve L 

We all have things we don't know or don't notice. Some of those things are about language and words. Only today it turned out I don't know the Polish name of a popular tabletop game - I saw a promotion for it, and I did not understand what "it" was: apparently it's a well known thing and a gimme for my wife.

Obviously as a foreigner I jump at any chance to show off my language skills to native speakers. I'm not really the good guy here 🤣

@Duffy 
I was at a Flyers game and saw a guy wearing an 88 jersey with MAMA'S BOY across the shoulders. Not universally loved here. Still, pretty impressive in the Legion of Doom line with Renberg and leClair.

@JohnWM
The local rumor is that Lindros got one of his concussions from a teammate, who was subsequently traded to the Hurricanes.

@Lewis 
Thanks to the comment reminder, I found and tackled your WaPo puzzle.  I did the NYT puzzle in twenty three minutes, with eight cheats, while the WaPo puzzle was done in sixteen minutes, and only four cheats (but many, many, many 'check grids".  Both were fun!
Thank you!

@Lewis 

Wapo xword spoiler below, beware!!!‼️

Apparently I'm not smart enough to solve yours and Rachel Fabi's crossword, but my wife is loving it. With her help I'm finally making serious progress. She really enjoyed your clue for dip 😍

@Lewis 

I found your and Rachel’s puzzle nicely challenging and satisfying. Well done!

However, I did it through the LAT because…Bezos. (Yes, I know that had absolutely zero effect on him. It was a me thing.)

@Warren 
While I was doing Lewis and Rachel's puzzle (which I found challenging and finishing required a nap), I saw that the Weds, Nov 27 puzzle was by Christina Iverson.  I'd rate it similar to a Times Wednesday. Any 
way, I couldn't access it on my WaPo app, but was able to access it from the LAT website.

@Lewis 

Thank you all for your comments re my LAT puzzle, which are so helpful in helping me improve my puzzle making.  It was a tough puzzle.  I hadn't looked at it in quite a while, and when I did it today it was no walk in the park!




Et tu emu.

@Lewis

TIL WaPo runs LAT puzzles. For a minute I thought (without doubt) you had two published on the same day!

I was excited to tell my dad that someone from the Comments (my new cult) constructed today's LAT puzzle, but they're delayed a week in his local paper. I expect you'll have new fans on 12/14!

@pitypie 
That was the hardest corner for me. Was unfamiliar with either spelling of the First Nation, refused to consider any alternative to JiM, and still have no idea what COD stands for. 
However, I did fill in the NE corner entirely and quickly with the Across clues.

@CaptainQuahog 

I think there’s a time limit for maintaining one’s streak, though I don’t know what it is. 

I didn’t solve the puzzle during the tech workers’ strike. As soon as they went back to work, I solved the first puzzle I had skipped — and got a blue star. 

@Elyse — I hope your recovery goes well.

@Renegator 

Right? This was my first thought, too. The more defenses there are, the more likely you are to lay siege to a place rather than storm it.

Still, I instantly knew what the answer would be so the clue worked, which makes it good.

@Andrzej 

Ahhh, you are smarter than I am.

I kept thinking the answer fit but it must be something else, given the logic.

